President Donald J. Trump has proclaimed April 9, 2018, as National Former Prisoner of War Recognition Day. This day honors the brave men and women who have been captured and held as prisoners of war during conflicts throughout American history. The proclamation recognizes several significant military anniversaries, including the centennial observance of the Armistice that ended World War I and the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Kasserine Pass in World War II. It also acknowledges the sacrifices and hardships endured by former POWs, including loneliness, torture, and separation from loved ones. The proclamation calls upon Americans to observe this day by honoring the service and sacrifice of all former prisoners of war and expresses the nation's gratitude for their sacrifice. It also encourages government officials and organizations to hold appropriate ceremonies and activities to commemorate this day.